22
00:01:17,230 --> 00:01:19,810

23
00:01:19,810 --> 00:01:22,280
Part a is true.

24
00:01:22,280 --> 00:01:25,130

25
00:01:25,130 --> 00:01:26,620
Why?

26
00:01:26,620 --> 00:01:31,490
Well, what does it mean for
A and B to be similar?

27
00:01:31,490 --> 00:01:37,810
Right, we know there's some
matrix M, such that-- that's

28
00:01:37,810 --> 00:01:40,660
what st means--

29
00:01:40,660 --> 00:01:45,260
when I multiply A on the left
by M and the right by M

30
00:01:45,260 --> 00:01:46,320
inverse,

31
00:01:46,320 --> 00:01:49,560
I get B. OK.

32
00:01:49,560 --> 00:01:57,080
So let's take that same matrix
M and multiply it on the left

33
00:01:57,080 --> 00:02:03,075
and the right of 2A cubed plus
A minus 3 times the identity.

34
00:02:03,075 --> 00:02:05,830

35
00:02:05,830 --> 00:02:06,630
OK.

36
00:02:06,630 --> 00:02:08,720
What do we get here?

37
00:02:08,720 --> 00:02:14,190
Well, the point is when A times
A cubed times m inverse,

38
00:02:14,190 --> 00:02:19,515
we can just write that
as 3 MAM inverses.

39
00:02:19,515 --> 00:02:24,190

40
00:02:24,190 --> 00:02:33,070
Similarly, we have an MAM
inverse and an M times the

41
00:02:33,070 --> 00:02:35,980
identity times m inverse.

42
00:02:35,980 --> 00:02:38,270
Good.

43
00:02:38,270 --> 00:02:41,920
Remember that M times A times M
inverse is B. So we just get

44
00:02:41,920 --> 00:02:49,800
2B cubed, 3B plus B minus--

45
00:02:49,800 --> 00:02:53,010
well, M times the identity is
just M. So we just get the

46
00:02:53,010 --> 00:02:57,872
identity back, and we have
3 times the identity.

47
00:02:57,872 --> 00:02:58,760
Good.

48
00:02:58,760 --> 00:03:02,280
And this is a general remark,
that if you have matrices A

49
00:03:02,280 --> 00:03:05,910
and B that are similar, then
any polynomials in these

50
00:03:05,910 --> 00:03:09,080
matrices A and B will
be similar.

51
00:03:09,080 --> 00:03:13,090
It's the exact same
